Leaving_camp: ^: I think it's time for me to say goodbye to you all.
^: Sadly, I don't feel at home being here.
^Nothing personal, but I feel the need to look for somewhere where I can feel at home.
^: I hope you look what you're looking for..
^: If we happen to meet again, I hope to be able to receive you guys with the same hospitality you showed me.
^: God damn it, he was the most hardworking of all of us.
Reaching_new_camp: ^: I think I'm all alone here. Bummer.
^: Hope I'll find some comapny soon.
Alone_by_bonfire: ^: Hope you don't mind me disturbing you a little bit with a campfire. I need to get warm by the night.
^: Let us see what tomorrow brings me. Nighty night, darkness.
Day_two: ^. And how should I call you?
^. Do you need a place to stay?
^: Got an empty nice space near my tent. If you wish to, make yourself confortable over there.
Day_three: ^: Actually, it was pretty smooth. Way smoothier than my days with the last group I tagged with
^: So you had company of another group, then?
^: Yeah, but life there was boring. It didn't feel like *home*, you know?
^: I felt detached and alone, so I parted ways and here I am.
^: Curious. Glad to see that I wasn't the only one.
^: So you don't want only to survive, but to live in a home truly yours as well. Nice.
^: I believe we can make a home together. Not just any camp, but a true home where we could feel cozy and confortable.
Day_four: ^: Yeah, but stay chill. We don't bite!
^: Yeah, gather around and make yourselves at home.
^: Are you guys around for a while?
^: It's been a while now. But don't worry, there is space for you to get comfy.
^: Oh well, thank you very much!
Day_five: ^: So, where are you guys from anyway?
^: We actually got out from the same camp.
^: Why have you guys left? Were you having trouble?
^: We got out for a very lame reason, actually, it doesn't even deserve mentioning.
^: The camp was functional, but being there was... How do I put it?
^: Made you feel unwanted, meaningless and not at home?
^: So we left after somewhere we could feel at home.
^: Oh boy, that's why we left our own groups and moved here!
^: Holy moly we weren't the only ones.
^: It's way more common that you'd imagine. There is no shame into looking for somewhere else you can feel good with yourself and the place you live in.
^: Once again, welcome to the group.
LikeWater0: ^: Before this all started, I used to live by the beach.
^: Went to sleep every night with the sound of crashing waves.
LikeWater1: ^: Can you feel it get a bit colder?
^: As a matter of fact, yes. Is that a bad thing?
^: Not at all, I love it. My favourite season is the winter.
LikeWater2: ^: I hope it rains tomorrow. The toads croak and the noise helps me to sleep.
^: In the middle of the wild?
^: The toads croak louder, it's great
DislikeWater0: ^: Have you ever dreamed about drowning?
^: Can't recall, I usually can't remember my dreams. Why is that?
^: I had this nightmare last night. It was terrible.
^: I do hope never need to swim, for it wouldn't be much different from that nightmare.
DislikeWater1: ^:  If and when you set out to gather food, please don't bring fish.
^:  Seriously, it smells awful. And the stench gets everywere. Please don't bring them.
DislikeWater2: ^: The end of society gave us a rather unexpected good thing.
^: Besides not having to worry about jobs, stocks and taxes?
^: No more alcohol. No more drunk people. No more that ethylic foul smell. Just wonderful.
LikeEarth0: ^: At this time of year, my grandpa used to take me hiking.
^: Yeah. Remembering him with his old cane always make me feel home.
^: Nice, I bet it was nice.
^: Actually I was the one who made all the hiking, he'd walk for half a mile and then stop.
LikeEarth1: ^: In any other scenery, I'd be gathering my crops by now.
^: Were you a gardner back in the day?
^: More like an enthusiast. I used to plant pumpkins in the mean time. They're spooky.
LikeEarth2: ^: So, how do you like my earrings?
^: They were a gift from my mama. She used to tinker with jewelry, and she made those specially for me back in the day.
^: It has diamonds engraved in the shape of a constellation.

s0: ^She would always say it would guide me to home.
s1: ^When I get lost, I look to it and search for the stars on the sky, so I know the way home.

DislikeEarth0: ^: ...What are you trying to tell me?
^: I really miss a broom to sweep the floor, or having a floor to sweep.
^: You know, cleaning something, not having dirt in all of your clothes.
^: Gosh, here I thought you were a witch!
DislikeEarth1: ^: You look like you want to ask something.
^: Indeed, I do. I may have never noticed, but I saw you limping?
^:When I was little, I fell from a cliff high enough to damage my knee. Since them I've been limping.
^: Yeah, ouch. Not a fan of cliffs since then.
DislikeEarth2: ^: Mind if I share something with you?
^: Don't make me go to the mine, please. When I was younger, I got stuck inside one for days.
^: Since then, closed, confined spaces has been specially unsettling
^: No need to worry, I'll remember that.
LikeFire0: ^: I'd do anything to light up a grill right now.
^: What would you grill in it?
^: Nothing in special, the greatest pleasure is lighting it up with two rocks and seeing the fire spread on the coal. It's so warming and comfy.
^: So... Lighting only for the sake of lighting?
LikeFire1: ^: You know what is the best part of winter?
^: The end of it. So spring may begin and the weather get warmer again
LikeFire2: ^: Are you feeling something different on the air?
^: You mean the bittersweet smell on the air the whole night?
^: Yes! Just got finished mixing some herbs and now I got a brand new incense. Did you like it?

s0: ^I actually liked it a lot, I only wish it wasn't as strong as it is right now
s1: ^Not exactly, is too much bitter and too much sweet. In the end is just a mess of differente smells begging for my attention.

LikeFire2: ^: I'll change the proportions and later I'll ask you again.
DislikeFire0: ^: The food was specially spicy tonight.
^: That's unexpected, I don't believe to have done anything different.
^: I wish I could make it less spicy. I mean, non-spicy at all.
^: But then it would be almost tasteless.
^: I disagree with that, your taste is already addicted to the pepper.
DislikeFire1: ^: You look like you want to ask something.
^: I saw something on your arm, and it got me wondering what was it.
^: It's a wound from when I was a kid.
^: Got burned with hot iron by accident and the mark never left.
^: That's alright, the mark makes me look cooler. Still would prefer not to get close to hot irons, though.
DislikeFire2: ^: Today is weirdly warm for an autumn night.
^: I wish I could make it cooler. Lift off this heavy sensation from the atmosphere, you know what I'm saying?
LikeAir0: ^: Windy nights like these always brings me memories from when I was a kid.
^: How I used to fly kites.
^: Yeah, I used to fly this big, bird-shaped, yellow kite. When the wind was right, it was the prettiest thing in the sky.
LikeAir1: ^: Jazz. Chet Bacon. Chicken Corea. John Colt-Raine. You know, jazz?
^: Sorry, not a clue. I'm actually pretty clueless about jazz.
LikeAir2: ^: Up there in the sky! And look, a hound!
^: Dude, are you aware that there are only clouds up there?
DislikeAir0: ^: Boogeyman? Mere trickery and boogeyman, I'd say. And your is?
^: Looking down and realizing I'm actually a couple of miles high. Gives me chills, dude.
DislikeAir1: ^: Another day I saw a kite.
^: Kite, like a kite that children fly?
^: Never got how to fly one, nor what is the fun of it. It's so pointless and uninteresting.
DislikeAir2: ^: Can I share something with you that makes me really unconfortable?
^: If a tornado hit us during the night, please hold me.
^: Tornados. They used to hit my hometown every now and then.
^: I remember my neighbor, a chicken, flying towards the sky because of it. Scares the heck out of me.
^: Don't worry, I'll tie you to a tree if a tornado hits us.
ProficienceWater0: ^: You see, these fish aren't as well prepared as they could be. I'm not complaining, but they could be something more tasteful.
^: Used to be a fisherman. Worked as a fisherman for years. There isn't a single way to cook fish that I don't know.
ProficienceWater1: ^: Oh boy, if we were back on my old town, I could serve you all the finest brew.
^: What were you, some kind of barman?
^: Precisely. I know better than anyone how some good ale is always welcome in company of good lads and good food.
ProficienceWater2: ^: Could we sing some sea shanties?
^: I don't think we know any.
^: Oh, don't worry, we have all night. I could teach you all some of the best ones for us to sing all night through.
ProficienceEarth0: ^: Being here outside brings me memories of new mown hay back at home.
^: Sittin' at the porch, smoking tobacco on my pipe, watching the crops, listening at the crickets at night.
^: Dayum, those were some good days.
^: Me? Not at all! I'm not sad because it's over, for I'm glad it happened and now I get to share my stories with some good folk!
ProficienceEarth1: ^: Back at the mines, we couldn't see the sky so clear like this.
^: Seeing something this starred and beautiful is breathtaking.
^: I bet the diamonds at the mine were prettier.
^: Nothing I've seen in any mine glittered as the stars at the night sky.
ProficienceEarth2: ^: Nights like this used to be the best ones to travel. So starred and bright, the path would always be clear almost entirely by the full moon.
^: Weren't you afraid of the dark?
^: I have nothing to fear under the full moon and a lit torch.
^: That must be a really interesting life. You must be full of fascinating stories.
^: Oh you can bet on it.
ProficienceFire0: ^: Guess who made the glass bottle you're holding right now.
^: I wish. I remember every bottle and cup I've blown, and this one was truly something.
^: I remember getting a pretty nasty burn on the upper lip with this one.
ProficienceFire1: ^: Whenever I close my eyes, I still listen to the whistle blowing.
^: Of the train I used to ride. Gigantic, powerful, masterfully crafted.
^: But it was hot. Heavens forgive me, but it was hot as hell.
ProficienceFire2: ^: A night like this used to make me feel inspired to craft horseshoes.
^: Actually, any kind of metalwork people payed me to do.
^: But mostly it was horsehoes. Horseshoes all day and night. People used to call me a master craftsman, but I don't quite buy it.
ProficienceAir0: ^: Tell me, you guys: do you dance?
^: I used to dance at fairs, but I'm not that good of a dancer.
^: There is no such thing as a bad dancer, you only need to feel the wind guide your limbs at the rhythm. Come on, dance with me.
^: Hah! Passing such an opportunity as dancing with a professional dancer like me. You must be out of your mind!
ProficienceAir1: ^: A fine night like this really makes you wish you had your trusty guitar with you.
^: Trusty guitar? What are you, a Bard?
^: I'm not just a bard, I'm the - - Well, I used to be the best bard around.
^: Such a shame my career was shortlived, but the world shall hear my voice for many more years!
ProficienceAir2: ^: Such a fine night with a fine wind as this would be great for me to conduct tests!
^: Tests to see how could I glide using mechanical wings!
^: Like a flying bird naturally do?
^: Yes, but imagine all of us being able to fly just like a parakeet! I used to work on that, but my progress has been halted for a while.
^: I'm sure you'll get back to work on your project soon enough.
BarkFood0: ^: Don't sweat it, I'll be back with a tasty dinner soon enough!
BarkFood1: ^: I'll be back until night with food, don't worry.
BarkFood2: ^: Do any of you don't eat meat? Just checking.
BarkDebrie1: ^: Don't mind the mess, I'll be over soon enough with this.
BarkDebrie2: ^: Where do I dispose of all of this?
BarkWater0: ^: I'm listening to the sea waves crashing already!
BarkWater1: ^: Are seashells still on fashion? I hope they do!
BarkWater2: ^: Hope I'm lucky enough to find a seashell that sounds like the sea.
BarkAir0: ^: Do any of you have seen a dodo yet? I'd love to see one someday.
BarkAir1: ^: If I ask nice enough, would a peacock lend me some of its feathers?
BarkAir2: ^: Do any of you want to join me? I'll let you ask the bird for feathers!.
BarkFire0: ^: Wild flowers do make the best incenses, I'll show you.
BarkFire1: ^: Tonight I'll light something different, I hope it does smells nice.
BarkFire2: ^: You guys are sure you don't mind me lighting my incenses?
BarkEarth0: ^: Heigh-ho, heigh-ho, from home to work we go!
BarkEarth1: ^: I've already seen topaz, ruby, opala, lapis-lazuli, emerald and amethyst on these mines.
BarkEarth2: ^: Sometimes I wish I had built a tunnel from here already.
BarkWood0: ^: How many planks one need to make a canoe?
BarkWood1: ^: Someday, I'll take one of you so we can chop a tree and make a boat.
BarkWood2: ^: Okay, beside the campfire, do you guys want more wood?
BarkStone0: ^: Another day I saw a pile of tiny rocks, they were the cutest thing.
BarkStone1: ^: I've heard the best houses are built on stones, I hope the best homes do.
BarkStone2: ^: I'll look to bring home a fossile tonight.
Strike0: ^: Today was a bad day, but tomorrow will be better. I'm betting on it.
Strike1: ^: The last two days were pretty awful. I hope it changes soon.
Strike2: ^: I'm starting to feel that it didn't matter to leave my old group. Anywhere I go is the same thing.
StrikeBark0: ^: Leaving takes only two steps: a dose of courage and a couple of steps.
StrikeBark1: ^: I'm starting to ponder if it's worth to waste time here.
StrikeBark2: ^: Tomorrow I'll leave. I'm only waiting for when the time is right.
StrikeLoss0: ^: I guess it only takes time for things to get better.
StrikeLoss1: ^: Okay, today was pretty alright. Let's do it tomorrow again!
StrikeLoss2: ^: There's no place like home for some self-healing.
LosingMember0: ^: I can't do this anymore. I know you tried your best, but I can't just be here. It's like nothing has changed from the last camp I've been.
^: I'm sorry we couldn't make it better for you.
^, it's nobody's fault. I just didn't manage to fit in, that's all.
LosingMember1: ^: My time has come to leave, my friends.
^: Are you sure of venturing out like this?
^: Yes, I don't belong here. I don't feel like home. But I hope to see you all soon around.
LosingMember2: ^, I'm leaving. I'm sorry for not telling anyone about it before, but I can't stand being in this camp anymore.
^: For how long have you been thinking about it?
^: A while now. I can't stay at a place where I don't feel like home.
^: I see. That's why we all came here, right?
